sentences: Rika Zaraï (Hebrew: ריקה זראי; 19 February 1938 – 23 December 2020) was a Franco-Israeli singer and writer.
Her father came from Odessa (now Ukraine) in the Russian Empire, and her mother from Valozhyn (now Belarus), then in Poland.
She passed her baccalaureate at the age of 17 and obtained her immediate military service, beating the call by one year.
During the 18 months of the army, she was appointed music producer in a group of the army of the center.
The singer sank into a coma for six days and remained immobilized for eight months in a shell of plaster.
Despite a reserved medical prognosis, she recovered completely after three years.
After having studied unconventional medicine for eleven years, she published under her name in 1985 a book Ma médecine naturelle (in english My natural medicine), which sells 2 million copies.
She sang at the Queen in Paris in 2000, and the oriental version of Hava nagila was successful in nightclubs where she sang until 2004.
On February 3, 2020, twelve years after her stroke, she sang in public during the Night of the Depression party organized by Raphaël Mezrahi at the Folies Bergère in Paris.
